.title = "Juicing the Yoneda Lemma",
.date = @date("2027-07-21T14:00:00-04:00"),
.author = "Robbie Lyman",
.layout = "post.shtml",
.draft = true,
---

The Yoneda Lemma is perhaps the most famous result in category theory.
One way of interpreting it is to say that you can reconstruct,
up to isomorphism, an object in a category from its web of connections
with other objects in that category.

Category theory being the favorite pasttime of smart nerds
afraid to get their hands dirty with the real work of mathematics
(I should know, this describes me more often than note),
it's easy to dismiss this observation as clever abstract nonsense,
but there's really quite a lot of mileage you can get out of it.
[Emily Riehl][Riehl] gives a great example in her excellent book [Category Theory In Context][Cat],
using the "universal property" (see below) of the tensor product of two vector spaces
to sketch how one might come up with the usual construction with "formal" tensors.

As a group theorist interested more and more in topological groups,
I'd like to attempt to do the same thing for free constructions on groups and topological groups.

## The Yoneda Lemma

I'm going to pick up where my [previous post]($link.page('blog/category-theory-day-one')) left off.
Recall that for each locally small category [`C`]($mathtex) with object [`c`]($mathtex),
we have a functor [`C(c,-) \colon C \to \mathrm{Set}`]($mathtex),
sending an object [`d`]($mathtex) to the set of arrows [`\{ f\colon c \to d \}`]($mathtex).

Moreover, if [`F \colon C \to \mathrm{Set}`]($mathtex) is an arbitrary set-valued functor,
the Yoneda Lemma states that there is a natural bijection between natural transformations
[`\alpha \colon C(c,-) \Rightarrow F`]($mathtex) and elements of the set [`Fc`]($mathtex)
accomplished by sending a natural transformation [`\alpha`]($mathtex)
to the element [`\alpha_c(1_c) \in Fc`]($mathtex).

A _universal property_ of an object [`c \in C`]($mathtex)
is a functor [`F \colon C \to \mathrm{Set}`]($mathtex)
and an element [`x \in Fc`]($mathtex) such that the corresponding natural transformation
[`\alpha(x) \colon C(c,-) \Rightarrow F`]($mathtex)
provided by the Yoneda Lemma is a natural _isomorphism._

## The Universal Property of the Free Group

For example, suppose that [`X`]($mathtex) is a set.
Given a group [`G`]($mathtex),
we can associate to it the set of functions [`X \to G`]($mathtex);
you can check that this association is functorial:
the action of a homomorphism of groups [`G \to H`]($mathtex) induces
a map from the set of functions [`X \to G`]($mathtex)
to the set of functions [`X \to H`]($mathtex).

The _free group on the set [`X`]($mathtex),_
which I'll denote [`F(X)`]($mathtex),
has the universal property expressed by this functor
and a particular function [`\iota\colon X \to F(X)`]($mathtex).

What this means in plainer terms is that any map [`f\colon X \to G`]($mathtex)
from the set [`X`]($mathtex) to a group [`G`]($mathtex),
corresponds (via the natural isomorphism)
to a unique group homomorphism [`\Phi\colon F(X) \to G`]($mathtex).

In terms of natural transformations of functors, we have the following,
where both vertical arrows are post-composition with [`\Phi`]($mathtex).
```=mathtex
\begin{CD}
\mathrm{Grp}(F(X), F(X)) @>{\cong}>> \mathrm{Set}(X, F(X)) \\
@V{\Phi_*}VV @VV{\Phi_*}V \\
\mathrm{Grp}(F(X), G) @>{\cong}>> \mathrm{Set}(X, G).
\end{CD}
```
If we trace the identity of [`F(X)`]($mathtex) around this diagram,
going right and down sends it first to [`\iota\colon X \to F(X)`]($mathtex)
and then to [`\Phi \circ \iota`]($mathtex),
while going down first and then right
yields [`f\colon X \to G`]($mathtex) by assumption.

In other words,
every function of sets [`f\colon X \to G`]($mathtex)
comes from (or extends to) a homomorphism of groups [`\Phi \colon F(X) \to G`]($mathtex).

## Using a little juice

So far so abstract.
Let's get a bit more concrete.
First, the map [`\iota`]($mathtex) is injective,
since if [`x \ne y`]($mathtex),
there is a function, say [`f\colon X \to \mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}`]($mathtex),
where [`f(x) = 0`]($mathtex) but [`f(y) = 1`]($mathtex).
Since this function is accomplished by a homomorphism [`\Phi\colon F(X) \to \mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}`]($mathtex),
we see that [`\iota(x) \ne \iota(y)`]($mathtex),
because their images under [`\Phi`]($mathtex) must be distinct.

Actually, this observation has the interesting immediate
_consequence_ of proving that for each cardinality [`\kappa`]($mathtex),
there exists a group [`G`]($mathtex) of cardinality at least [`\kappa`]($mathtex).

In light of the above, I will henceforth think of [`X`]($mathtex)
as a _subset_ of [`F(X)`]($mathtex) via the canonical injective function [`\iota`]($mathtex),
since there is no further risk of confusion.

Next, we can use the Yoneda lemma to show that the subgroup of [`F(X)`]($mathtex)
_normally generated_ by [`X`]($mathtex) is all of [`F(X)`]($mathtex).
 Call this subgroup [`N`]($mathtex).
By construction, the quotient map [`F(X) \to F(X)/N`]($mathtex)
agrees on [`X`]($mathtex) with the function [`X \to F(X)/N`]($mathtex) sending each element to the identity.
But so does the trivial homomorphism sending _every_ element of [`F(X)`]($mathtex) to the identity of [`F(X)/N`]($mathtex).
By the universal property, then, these homomorphisms are equal,
which implies that [`N = F(X)`]($mathtex).

Let's be even a little more clever:
let's show that [`\langle X \rangle = F(X)`]($mathtex) without needing to take normal closures.
Suppose not, so that there is [`g \notin \langle X \rangle`]($mathtex).
Consider the two functions [`f_1`]($mathtex) and [`f_2`]($mathtex) of sets [`F(X) \to F(X)`]($mathtex)
defined so that both are the identity everywhere except [`g`]($mathtex), and that
[`f_1(g) = g`]($mathtex) and [`f_2(g) = 1`]($mathtex).
These correspond to homomorphisms [`\Phi_1`]($mathtex) and [`\Phi_2\colon F(F(X)) \to F(X)`]($mathtex).
Composing with the homomorphism [`I \colon F(X) \to F(F(X))`]($mathtex)
given by the inclusion of [`X`]($mathtex) into [`F(X)`]($mathtex),
we see that [`f_1 \circ I`]($mathtex) is the identity (which implies [`I`]($mathtex) is injective),
and that [`(f_1 \circ I)_X = (f_2 \circ I)|_X`]($mathtex),
so these homomorphisms are equal.

[Riehl]: https://emilyriehl.github.io/
[Cat]: https://emilyriehl.github.io/files/context.pdf
